Service Agreement For Network Integration Transmission Service
THIS AGREEMENT is made this 6th day of August 2004 by and between Green Mountain Power Corporation (hereinafter called "GMP" or the "Transmission Provider"), and Vermont Electric Cooperative, Inc. (hereinafter called "VEC" or the "Transmission Customer"). In consideration of the mutual covenants and agreements herein contained, the Parties hereto agree as follows: 1. The Transmission Provider agrees to furnish, and the Transmission Customer agrees to take and pay for, Network Integration Transmission Service pursuant to the Transmission Provider's FERC Transmission Service Tariff No. 7 ("Tariff"), as modified from time to time. The terms and conditions of the Tariff are incorporated herein and made a part hereof. Nothing contained herein shall be construed as affecting in any way the Transmission Provider's right to unilaterally make application to the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission, or other regulatory agency having jurisdiction, for any change in the Tariff or this Service Agreement under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act, or other applicable statute, and any rules and regulations promulgated thereunder; or the Transmission Customer's rights under the Federal Power Act and rules and regulations promulgated thereunder. 2. Specifications for service under this Service Agreement agreed to by the Transmission Provider and the Transmission Customer are attached hereto. 3. This Service Agreement shall not be assigned. 4. This Service Agreement is subject to any present and future state and federal laws, regulations, orders or other duly promulgated requirements.
5. This Service Agreement shall become effective on July 15, 2004 and shall continue in effect thereafter until terminated with one year's written notice by either party; provided that, unless this service agreement is superseded by another service agreement providing for the Transmission Customer to take and pay for transmission service over the facilities specified in this paragraph, the Transmission Customer shall pay to the Transmission Provider, within fifteen (15) days of the rendering of the bill, (a) the undepreciated cost, as of upon the termination date, of (i) any distribution facilities of Transmission Provider designated in Specification No. 2 to this Service Agreement, and (ii) the specific meter and meter-related plant that are the basis for the Delivery Point Cost charged by the Transmission Provider to the Transmission Customer as provided under Attachment H-3 to the Tariff; and (b) the cost of dismantling and removing the facilities and plant listed in (a) above.
IN WITNESS HEREOF, the Parties have caused this Service Agreement to be executed by their respective authorized officials.

Network Operating Agreement
This Network Operating Agreement by and between Green Mountain Power Corporation ("GMP" or the "Transmission Provider") and Vermont Electric Cooperative, Inc. ("VEC" or the "Transmission Customer") is an implementing agreement for Network Integration Transmission Service under the Transmission Provider's open access transmission tariff (the "Network Tariff") and is subject to and a part of the Network Tariff. All definitions, terms and conditions of the Network Tariff are incorporated herein by reference. 1. General Terms and Conditions: The Transmission Provider agrees to provide transmission service to the Transmission Customer's equipment or facilities, subject to the Transmission Customer operating its facilities in accordance with applicable criteria, rules, standards, procedures, and guidelines of the Transmission Provider, its Affiliates, VELCO, ISO New England and its successors in interest as administrator of the NEPOOL markets as defined in the Restated NEPOOL Agreement dated September 1971 as amended from time to time, and Northeast Power Coordinating Council ("NPCC") as they may be adopted and/or amended from time to time. In addition to the provisions defined in those documents, service to the Transmission Customer's equipment or facilities is provided subject to the following specified terms and conditions. a. Electrical Supply: The electrical supply to the Point(s) of Delivery shall be in the form of three-phase sixty hertz alternating current at a voltage class determined by mutual agreement of the parties. b. Coordination of Operations: The Transmission Provider shall consult with the Transmission Customer regarding timing of scheduled maintenance of the Transmission System. In the event of a curtailment of service or the implementation of load shedding procedures, the Transmission Provider shall use due diligence to resume delivery of electric power as quickly as possible. 2. Reporting Obligations: a. The Transmission Customer shall be responsible for all information required by NPCC, ISO New England, VELCO, and the Transmission Provider's dispatching functions. The Transmission Customer shall respond promptly and completely to the Transmission Provider's requests for information as it relates to network integration transmission service and distribution service, including, but not limited to, data necessary for operations, maintenance, regulatory requirements and analysis. In particular, that information may include: i. For Network Loads: 10-year annual peak load forecast, load power factor performance, under frequency load shedding capability, load shedding capability, disturbance/interruption reports; protection system setting conformance; system testing and maintenance conformance; planned changes to protection systems; metering testing and maintenance conformance; planned changes in transformation capability; conformance to harmonic and voltage fluctuation limits; dead station tripping conformance; and, voltage reduction capability conformance. ii. For Network Resources and interconnected generators as they relate to network integration transmission service and distribution service: 10-year forecast of generation capacity retirements and additions; generator reactive capability verification; generator under frequency relaying conformance; protection system testing and maintenance conformance; planned changes to protection system; and planned changes to generation parameters. b. The Transmission Customer shall supply accurate and reliable information to the system operators regarding available metered values for MW, MVAR, volt, amp, frequency, breaker status indication as it relates to network integration transmission service and distribution service and all other information deemed necessary by the Transmission Provider for safe and reliable operation. Information will be exchanged electronically where possible. 3. Operational Obligations at Point(s) of Delivery: The Transmission Customer shall request permission from the system operators prior to opening and/or closing circuit breakers, which could impact the Transmission Provider's service, per applicable switching and operating procedures. The Transmission Customer shall carry out all switching orders from the Transmission Provider, VELCO, ISO New England, or the Transmission Provider's designee in a timely manner. a. The Transmission Customer shall reasonably balance the load at the Point(s) of Delivery such that the differences in the individual phase currents are acceptable to the Transmission Provider. b. The Transmission Customer's equipment shall conform with harmonic distortion and voltage fluctuation standards that conform to Good Utility Practice. c. The Transmission Customer's equipment must comply with all applicable Federal and State environmental requirements to the extent they impact the operation of the Transmission Provider's system. d. The Transmission Customer shall operate all of its equipment and facilities connected to the Transmission Provider's system in a safe and efficient manner and in accordance with Good Utility Practice. e. The Transmission Customer is responsible for supplying voltage regulation equipment on its subtransmission and distribution facilities. 4. Notice of Transmission Service Interruptions: If at any time, in the reasonable exercise of the system operator's judgment, operation of the Transmission Customer's equipment adversely affects the quality of service or interferes with the safe and reliable operation of the system, the Transmission Provider may discontinue transmission service until the condition has been corrected. Unless the system operators perceive that an emergency exists or the risk of an emergency is imminent, the system operators shall give the Transmission Customer reasonable notice of its intention to discontinue transmission service and, where practical, allow suitable time for the Transmission Customer to remove the interfering condition. The Transmission Provider's judgment with regard to the discontinuance of service under this paragraph shall be made in accordance with Good Utility Practice. In the case of such discontinuance, the Transmission Provider shall immediately confer with the Transmission Customer regarding the conditions causing such discontinuance and its recommendation concerning timely correction thereof. 5. Access and Control: Properly accredited representatives of the Transmission Provider shall at all reasonable times have access to the Transmission Customer's facilities to make reasonable inspections and obtain information required in connection with this Network Tariff. Such representatives shall provide reasonable advance notice as well as make themselves known to the Transmission Customer's personnel, state the object of their visit, and conduct themselves in a manner that will not interfere with the construction or operation of the Transmission Customer's facilities. The Transmission Provider will have control such that it may open or close the circuit breaker or disconnect and place safety grounds at the Point(s) of Delivery, or at the station, if the Point(s) of Delivery is remote from the station for emergency situations or mutually agreed planned operations. 6. Point(s) of Delivery or Remote Delivery Point(s): Network Transmission service will be delivered by the Transmission Provider at the Point(s) of Delivery as specified in the Customer's Service Agreement, and as amended from time to time. Each Point of Delivery shall have a unique identifier, meter location, meter number, metered voltage, terms on meter compensation and, the actual or, if not currently in service, the projected in service year. 7. Maintenance of Equipment at Point(s) of Delivery: a. Unless otherwise agreed, the Transmission Provider will own all metering equipment. b. The Transmission Customer shall maintain all of its equipment and facilities connected to the Transmission Provider's system in a safe and efficient manner and in accordance with manufacturers' recommendations, Good Utility Practice, applicable regulations, and requirements of the Transmission Provider, VELCO, ISO New England, and NPCC. c. The Transmission Provider may request that the Transmission Customer test, calibrate, verify or validate the data link, metering, data acquisition, transmission, protective, or other equipment or software owned by the Transmission Customer, consistent with the Transmission Customer's routine obligation to maintain its equipment and facilities, or for the purposes of trouble shooting problems on the network facilities. The Transmission Customer will be responsible for the cost to test, calibrate, verify or validate the equipment or software. d. The Transmission Provider shall have the right to inspect the tests, calibrations, verifications and validations of the Transmission Customer's data link, metering, data acquisition, transmission, protective, or other equipment or other software connected to the Transmission Provider's system. e. The Transmission Customer, at the Transmission Provider's request, shall supply the Transmission Provider with a copy of the installation, test, and calibration records of the data link, metering, data acquisition, transmission, protective, or other equipment or other software owned by the Transmission Customer and connected to the Transmission Provider's system. f. The Transmission Provider shall have the right, at the Transmission Customer's expense, to monitor the factory acceptance test, the field acceptance test, and the installation of any metering, data acquisition, transmission, protective or other equipment or software installed on facilities directly connected to the Transmission Provider's system. 8. Emergency System Operations: a. The Transmission Customer's equipment and facilities as they relate to network integration transmission service and distribution service shall be subject to all applicable emergency operation standards consistent with Good Utility Practice required of and by the Transmission Provider to operate in an interconnected transmission network. b. The Transmission Provider reserves the right to have the system operators take whatever actions or inactions they deem reasonably necessary during emergency operating conditions to: (i) preserve the integrity of the Transmission System, (ii) limit or prevent damage, (iii) expedite restoration of service, or (iv) preserve public safety. 9. Cost Responsibility: The Transmission Customer shall be responsible for all reasonable costs incurred by the Transmission Provider relative to the Transmission Customer's facilities and in accordance with Good Utility Practice. Some costs may be allocated to several Transmission Customers. If the method for allocating costs is not clearly defined, then the method for allocation will be at the Transmission Provider's discretion. 10. Service For a Network Resource: The following Terms and Conditions apply to service for any new or future generator Network Resource as it relates to network integration transmission service and distribution service. a. Voltage or Reactive Control Requirements: i. Unless directed otherwise, the Transmission Customer will operate its interconnected generation facility(ies) with an automatic voltage regulator(s). The voltage regulator will control voltage at the Point(s) of Receipt consistent with the range of voltage scheduled by the Transmission Provider, the Transmission Provider's agent, VELCO, or ISO New England. ii. At the discretion of the Transmission Provider, the Transmission Provider's agent, VELCO, or ISO New England, the Transmission Customer may be directed to deactivate the automatic voltage regulator and to supply reactive power per a schedule provided by the Transmission Provider, the Transmission Provider's agent, VELCO, or ISO New England. iii. If the Transmission Customer has not installed capacity sufficient to operate its generation facility consistent with recommendations of the Transmission Provider resulting from the System Impact and Facilities Studies or fails to operate at such capacity, the Transmission Provider may install, at the Transmission Customer's expense, reactive compensation equipment necessary to ensure the proper voltage or reactive supply at the Point(s) of Receipt. b. Station Service: When the Transmission Customer's generation facility that is directly connected to the Transmission Provider's system is producing electricity, the Transmission Customer's generation facility must supply its own station service power. If and when the Transmission Customer's generation facility that is directly connected to the Transmission Provider's system is not producing electricity, the Transmission Customer's generation facility must obtain station service capacity and energy from the retail franchise utility providing service. Station Service will comply with NESC and will not be tied in such a way that a backfeed into the Transmission Provider's system can occur. c. Protection Requirements: Protection requirements are defined in the Transmission Provider's standard interconnection contract and in VELCO, ISO New England, and NPCC documents as may be adopted or amended from time to time. d. Operational Obligations: i. ISO New England may require the generators to be equipped for Automatic Generation Control ("AGC"). The Transmission Customer will be responsible for all costs associated with installing and maintaining an AGC system on the Transmission Customer's generators that are directly connected to the Transmission Provider's system. ii. The Transmission Provider retains the right to require reduced generation at times when system conditions present transmission restrictions or otherwise adversely affect the Transmission Provider's other customers. The Transmission Provider will use due diligence to resolve the problems to allow the generator to return to the operating level prior to the Transmission Provider's notice to reduce generation. iii. All operations (including start-up, shutdown and determination of hourly generation) for generators directly connected to the Transmission Provider's system will be coordinated with ISO New England, VELCO, or the Transmission Provider's Designated Agent. e. Coordination of Operations: i. The Transmission Customer shall furnish the Transmission Provider with generator annual maintenance schedules and advise the Transmission Provider if its Network Resource is capable of participation in system restoration and/or if it has black start capability. ii. The Transmission Provider reserves the right to specify turbine and/or generator control (e.g., droop) settings as determined by the System Impact or Facilities Study or subsequent studies. The Transmission Customer agrees to comply with such specifications by the Transmission Provider at the Transmission Customer's expense. iii. If the generator is not dispatchable by ISO New England, the Transmission Customer shall notify the Transmission Provider at least 48 hours in advance of its intent to take its resource temporarily off-line and its intent to resume generation. In circumstances such as forced outages, the Transmission Customer shall notify the Transmission Provider as promptly as possible of the Network Resource's temporary interruption of generation and/or transmission. 11. Service for Delivery to Load: The following Terms and Conditions are specific to Service for Delivery to Load: a. Power Factor Requirement: The Transmission Customer agrees to maintain an overall Load Power Factor and reactive power supply within predefined sub-areas as measured at the Point(s) of Delivery within ranges specified by the Transmission Provider, VELCO, and ISO New England criteria, rules and standards consistent with Good Utility Practice which identify the power factor levels that must be maintained throughout the applicable sub-area for each anticipated level of total NEPOOL load. The Transmission Customer agrees to maintain Load Power Factor and reactive power requirements within the range specified by the Transmission Provider, VELCO, and ISO New England as appropriate for the sub-area based on total NEPOOL load during that hour. ISO New England may revise the power factor limits required from time to time. If the Transmission Customer lacks the capability to maintain the Load Power Factor within the ranges specified, the Transmission Provider may install, at the Transmission Customer's expense, reactive compensation equipment necessary to ensure proper load power factor at the Point(s) of Delivery. b. Protection Requirements: The Transmission Customer's relay and protection systems at the point(s) of delivery must comply with all applicable Transmission Provider, VELCO, ISO New England, and NPCC criteria, rules, procedures, guidelines, standards and requirements as may be adopted or amended from time to time and in accordance with Good Utility Practice. c. Operational Obligations: The Transmission Customer shall be responsible for operating and maintaining security of its electric system in a manner that avoids adverse impact to the Transmission Provider's or others' interconnected systems and complies with all applicable Transmission Provider, VELCO, ISO New England, and NPCC operating criteria, rules, procedures, guidelines and interconnection standards as may be amended or adopted from time to time. These actions include, but are not limited to: Voltage Reduction Load Shedding; Under Frequency Load Shedding; Block Load Shedding; Dead Station Tripping; Transferring Load Between Point(s) of Delivery; Implementing Voluntary Load Reductions Including Interruptible Customers; Starting Stand-by Generation; Permitting Transmission Provider Controlled Service Restoration Following Supply Delivery Contingencies on Transmission Provider Facilities. 12. Failure to perform: If the Transmission Customer fails to carry out its obligations under this Agreement the matter will be subject to the dispute resolution procedures of Section 12 of the Network Tariff. 13. System Operations: Notwithstanding any of the above, the following specific operating procedures must be adhered to. All safety and communication protocols will be maintained. a. Lines of Communication: The Transmission Customer will provide contact information to the Transmission Provider for operation of the systems. b. Operational Control: The Transmission Provider shall have full and exclusive operational control of all switches and equipment that connect the systems of the Transmission Provider and Transmission Customer. c. Separation: The Transmission Provider, at its sole discretion, shall install a means of separation of the interconnected systems at the Transmission Customer's sole expense. 14. System Maps and Updates: The Transmission Customer shall provide to the Transmission Provider electrical diagrams and routine updates of the Transmission Customer's system as it relates to the point(s) of delivery in support of the safe, reliable operations of the interconnected systems.
The Parties whose authorizing signatures appear below warrant that they will abide by the foregoing terms and conditions.

EXECUTIVE OFFICES 121 WEST STREET RUTLAND, VERMONT
New York State Electric & Gas Corporation Chatham New York
Gentlemen:
We propose to furnish electricity to you at the Vermont-New York State Line on State Highway No. 346 in the form of single phase, 60 cycles, alternating current at approximately 2300 volts in order that you may supply the Paddock Farm located on said highway approximately 700 feet west of the State Line in the Town of Petersburg.
This proposal is contingent on your obtaining for us a signed copy certificate from the Rensselaer County USDA War Board authorizing the construction of a line 1100 feet in length to reach the Paddock Farm.
Electricity will be supplied to you for the Paddock Farm at the State Line on the same terms as we would supply a farm customer located at that point. The monthly minimum charge will be $2.00 for a period of five years, and as long as the service is used only to supply the Paddock Farm, billing will be rendered on our Rate A-2, a copy of which is attached. For billing purposes we will accept the consumption shown by your meter installed at the Paddock Farm, but to compensate for line and transformer losses between the State Line and the Paddock Farm we will add 15% to the monthly consumption at the farm. We shall have the right to request a test of such meters as you install and the privilege of having our representative present at such tests.
We reserve the option to install a primary meter at the State Line. If more than one customer is supplied by you from this source, the billing will be on an appropriate general rate in our Vermont tariff.
This arrangement shall be subject to the approval of state and federal regulatory bodies having jurisdiction.
This letter is submitted in duplicate and if it meets with your approval, we request that you sign the duplicate in the space provided, indicating your acceptance and return it to us.
Very truly yours,
GREEN MOUNTAIN POWER CORPORATION

Network Operating Agreement
This Network Operating Agreement by and between Green Mountain Power Corporation ("GMP" or the "Transmission Provider") and the Village of Hyde Park Water and Light Department ("Hyde Park" or the "Transmission Customer") is an implementing agreement for Network Integration Transmission Service under the Transmission Provider's open access transmission tariff (the "Network Tariff") and is subject to and a part of the Network Tariff. All definitions, terms and conditions of the Network Tariff are incorporated herein by reference. 1. General Terms and Conditions: The Transmission Provider agrees to provide transmission service to the Transmission Customer's equipment or facilities, subject to the Transmission Customer operating its facilities in accordance with applicable criteria, rules, standards, procedures, and guidelines of the Transmission Provider, its Affiliates, VELCO, ISO New England and its successors in interest as administrator of the NEPOOL markets as defined in the Restated NEPOOL Agreement dated September 1971 as amended from time to time, and Northeast Power Coordinating Council ("NPCC") as they may be adopted and/or amended from time to time. In addition to the provisions defined in those documents, service to the Transmission Customer's equipment or facilities is provided subject to the following specified terms and conditions. a. Electrical Supply: The electrical supply to the Point(s) of Delivery shall be in the form of three-phase sixty hertz alternating current at a voltage class determined by mutual agreement of the parties. b. Coordination of Operations: The Transmission Provider shall consult with the Transmission Customer regarding timing of scheduled maintenance of the Transmission System. In the event of a curtailment of service or the implementation of load shedding procedures, the Transmission Provider shall use due diligence to resume delivery of electric power as quickly as possible. 2. Reporting Obligations: a. The Transmission Customer shall be responsible for all information required by NPCC, ISO New England, VELCO, and the Transmission Provider's dispatching functions. The Transmission Customer shall respond promptly and completely to the Transmission Provider's requests for information as it relates to network integration transmission service and distribution service, including, but not limited to, data necessary for operations, maintenance, regulatory requirements and analysis. In particular, that information may include: i. For Network Loads: 10-year annual peak load forecast, load power factor performance, under frequency load shedding capability, load shedding capability, disturbance/interruption reports; protection system setting conformance; system testing and maintenance conformance; planned changes to protection systems; metering testing and maintenance conformance; planned changes in transformation capability; conformance to harmonic and voltage fluctuation limits; dead station tripping conformance; and, voltage reduction capability conformance. ii. For Network Resources and interconnected generators as they relate to network integration transmission service and distribution service: 10-year forecast of generation capacity retirements and additions; generator reactive capability verification; generator under frequency relaying conformance; protection system testing and maintenance conformance; planned changes to protection system; and planned changes to generation parameters. b. The Transmission Customer shall supply accurate and reliable information to the system operators regarding available metered values for MW, MVAR, volt, amp, frequency, breaker status indication as it relates to network integration transmission service and distribution service and all other information deemed necessary by the Transmission Provider for safe and reliable operation. Information will be exchanged electronically where possible. 3. Operational Obligations at Point(s) of Delivery: The Transmission Customer shall request permission from the system operators prior to opening and/or closing circuit breakers, which could impact the Transmission Provider's service, per applicable switching and operating procedures. The Transmission Customer shall carry out all switching orders from the Transmission Provider, VELCO, ISO New England, or the Transmission Provider's designee in a timely manner. a. The Transmission Customer shall reasonably balance the load at the Point(s) of Delivery such that the differences in the individual phase currents are acceptable to the Transmission Provider. b. The Transmission Customer's equipment shall conform with harmonic distortion and voltage fluctuation standards that conform to Good Utility Practice. c. The Transmission Customer's equipment must comply with all applicable Federal and State environmental requirements to the extent they impact the operation of the Transmission Provider's system. d. The Transmission Customer shall operate all of its equipment and facilities connected to the Transmission Provider's system in a safe and efficient manner and in accordance with Good Utility Practice. e. The Transmission Customer is responsible for supplying voltage regulation equipment on its subtransmission and distribution facilities. 4. Notice of Transmission Service Interruptions: If at any time, in the reasonable exercise of the system operator's judgment, operation of the Transmission Customer's equipment adversely affects the quality of service or interferes with the safe and reliable operation of the system, the Transmission Provider may discontinue transmission service until the condition has been corrected. Unless the system operators perceive that an emergency exists or the risk of an emergency is imminent, the system operators shall give the Transmission Customer reasonable notice of its intention to discontinue transmission service and, where practical, allow suitable time for the Transmission Customer to remove the interfering condition. The Transmission Provider's judgment with regard to the discontinuance of service under this paragraph shall be made in accordance with Good Utility Practice. In the case of such discontinuance, the Transmission Provider shall immediately confer with the Transmission Customer regarding the conditions causing such discontinuance and its recommendation concerning timely correction thereof. 5. Access and Control: Properly accredited representatives of the Transmission Provider shall at all reasonable times have access to the Transmission Customer's facilities to make reasonable inspections and obtain information required in connection with this Network Tariff. Such representatives shall provide reasonable advance notice as well as make themselves known to the Transmission Customer's personnel, state the object of their visit, and conduct themselves in a manner that will not interfere with the construction or operation of the Transmission Customer's facilities. The Transmission Provider will have control such that it may open or close the circuit breaker or disconnect and place safety grounds at the Point(s) of Delivery, or at the station, if the Point(s) of Delivery is remote from the station for emergency situations or mutually agreed planned operations. 6. Point(s) of Delivery or Remote Delivery Point(s): Network Transmission service will be delivered by the Transmission Provider at the Point(s) of Delivery as specified in the Customer's Service Agreement, and as amended from time to time. Each Point of Delivery shall have a unique identifier, meter location, meter number, metered voltage, terms on meter compensation and, the actual or, if not currently in service, the projected in service year. 7. Maintenance of Equipment at Point(s) of Delivery: a. Unless otherwise agreed, the Transmission Provider will own all metering equipment. b. The Transmission Customer shall maintain all of its equipment and facilities connected to the Transmission Provider's system in a safe and efficient manner and in accordance with manufacturers' recommendations, Good Utility Practice, applicable regulations, and requirements of the Transmission Provider, VELCO, ISO New England, and NPCC. c. The Transmission Provider may request that the Transmission Customer test, calibrate, verify or validate the data link, metering, data acquisition, transmission, protective, or other equipment or software owned by the Transmission Customer, consistent with the Transmission Customer's routine obligation to maintain its equipment and facilities, or for the purposes of trouble shooting problems on the network facilities. The Transmission Customer will be responsible for the cost to test, calibrate, verify or validate the equipment or software. d. The Transmission Provider shall have the right to inspect the tests, calibrations, verifications and validations of the Transmission Customer's data link, metering, data acquisition, transmission, protective, or other equipment or other software connected to the Transmission Provider's system. e. The Transmission Customer, at the Transmission Provider's request, shall supply the Transmission Provider with a copy of the installation, test, and calibration records of the data link, metering, data acquisition, transmission, protective, or other equipment or other software owned by the Transmission Customer and connected to the Transmission Provider's system. f. The Transmission Provider shall have the right, at the Transmission Customer's expense, to monitor the factory acceptance test, the field acceptance test, and the installation of any metering, data acquisition, transmission, protective or other equipment or software installed on facilities directly connected to the Transmission Provider's system. 8. Emergency System Operations: a. The Transmission Customer's equipment and facilities as they relate to network integration transmission service and distribution service shall be subject to all applicable emergency operation standards consistent with Good Utility Practice required of and by the Transmission Provider to operate in an interconnected transmission network. b. The Transmission Provider reserves the right to have the system operators take whatever actions or inactions they deem reasonably necessary during emergency operating conditions to: (i) preserve the integrity of the Transmission System, (ii) limit or prevent damage, (iii) expedite restoration of service, or (iv) preserve public safety. 9. Cost Responsibility: The Transmission Customer shall be responsible for all reasonable costs incurred by the Transmission Provider relative to the Transmission Customer's facilities and in accordance with Good Utility Practice. Some costs may be allocated to several Transmission Customers. If the method for allocating costs is not clearly defined, then the method for allocation will be at the Transmission Provider's discretion. 10. Service For a Network Resource: The following Terms and Conditions apply to service for any new or future generator Network Resource as it relates to network integration transmission service and distribution service. a. Voltage or Reactive Control Requirements: i. Unless directed otherwise, the Transmission Customer will operate its interconnected generation facility(ies) with an automatic voltage regulator(s). The voltage regulator will control voltage at the Point(s) of Receipt consistent with the range of voltage scheduled by the Transmission Provider, the Transmission Provider's agent, VELCO, or ISO New England. ii. At the discretion of the Transmission Provider, the Transmission Provider's agent, VELCO, or ISO New England, the Transmission Customer may be directed to deactivate the automatic voltage regulator and to supply reactive power per a schedule provided by the Transmission Provider, the Transmission Provider's agent, VELCO, or ISO New England. iii. If the Transmission Customer has not installed capacity sufficient to operate its generation facility consistent with recommendations of the Transmission Provider resulting from the System Impact and Facilities Studies or fails to operate at such capacity, the Transmission Provider may install, at the Transmission Customer's expense, reactive compensation equipment necessary to ensure the proper voltage or reactive supply at the Point(s) of Receipt. b. Station Service: When the Transmission Customer's generation facility that is directly connected to the Transmission Provider's system is producing electricity, the Transmission Customer's generation facility must supply its own station service power. If and when the Transmission Customer's generation facility that is directly connected to the Transmission Provider's system is not producing electricity, the Transmission Customer's generation facility must obtain station service capacity and energy from the retail franchise utility providing service. Station Service will comply with NESC and will not be tied in such a way that a backfeed into the Transmission Provider's system can occur. c. Protection Requirements: Protection requirements are defined in the Transmission Provider's standard interconnection contract and in VELCO, ISO New England, and NPCC documents as may be adopted or amended from time to time. d. Operational Obligations: i. ISO New England may require the generators to be equipped for Automatic Generation Control ("AGC"). The Transmission Customer will be responsible for all costs associated with installing and maintaining an AGC system on the Transmission Customer's generators that are directly connected to the Transmission Provider's system. ii. The Transmission Provider retains the right to require reduced generation at times when system conditions present transmission restrictions or otherwise adversely affect the Transmission Provider's other customers. The Transmission Provider will use due diligence to resolve the problems to allow the generator to return to the operating level prior to the Transmission Provider's notice to reduce generation. iii. All operations (including start-up, shutdown and determination of hourly generation) for generators directly connected to the Transmission Provider's system will be coordinated with ISO New England, VELCO, or the Transmission Provider's Designated Agent. e. Coordination of Operations: i. The Transmission Customer shall furnish the Transmission Provider with generator annual maintenance schedules and advise the Transmission Provider if its Network Resource is capable of participation in system restoration and/or if it has black start capability. ii. The Transmission Provider reserves the right to specify turbine and/or generator control (e.g., droop) settings as determined by the System Impact or Facilities Study or subsequent studies. The Transmission Customer agrees to comply with such specifications by the Transmission Provider at the Transmission Customer's expense. iii. If the generator is not dispatchable by ISO New England, the Transmission Customer shall notify the Transmission Provider at least 48 hours in advance of its intent to take its resource temporarily off-line and its intent to resume generation. In circumstances such as forced outages, the Transmission Customer shall notify the Transmission Provider as promptly as possible of the Network Resource's temporary interruption of generation and/or transmission. 11. General Terms and Conditions: The Transmission Provider agrees to provide transmission service to the Transmission Customer's equipment or facilities, subject to the Transmission Customer operating its facilities in accordance with applicable criteria, rules, standards, procedures, and guidelines of the Transmission Provider, its Affiliates, VELCO, ISO New England and its successors in interest as administrator of the NEPOOL markets as defined in the Restated NEPOOL Agreement dated September 1971 as amended from time to time, and Northeast Power Coordinating Council ("NPCC") as they may be adopted and/or amended from time to time. In addition to the provisions defined in those documents, service to the Transmission Customer's equipment or facilities is provided subject to the following specified terms and conditions. a. Electrical Supply: The electrical supply to the Point(s) of Delivery shall be in the form of three-phase sixty hertz alternating current at a voltage class determined by mutual agreement of the parties. b. Coordination of Operations: The Transmission Provider shall consult with the Transmission Customer regarding timing of scheduled maintenance of the Transmission System. In the event of a curtailment of service or the implementation of load shedding procedures, the Transmission Provider shall use due diligence to resume delivery of electric power as quickly as possible. 2. Reporting Obligations: a. The Transmission Customer shall be responsible for all information required by NPCC, ISO New England, VELCO, and the Transmission Provider's dispatching functions. The Transmission Customer shall respond promptly and completely to the Transmission Provider's requests for information as it relates to network integration transmission service and distribution service, including, but not limited to, data necessary for operations, maintenance, regulatory requirements and analysis. In particular, that information may include: i. For Network Loads: 10-year annual peak load forecast, load power factor performance, under frequency load shedding capability, load shedding capability, disturbance/interruption reports; protection system setting conformance; system testing and maintenance conformance; planned changes to protection systems; metering testing and maintenance conformance; planned changes in transformation capability; conformance to harmonic and voltage fluctuation limits; dead station tripping conformance; and, voltage reduction capability conformance. ii. For Network Resources and interconnected generators as they relate to network integration transmission service and distribution service: 10-year forecast of generation capacity retirements and additions; generator reactive capability verification; generator under frequency relaying conformance; protection system testing and maintenance conformance; planned changes to protection system; and planned changes to generation parameters. b. The Transmission Customer shall supply accurate and reliable information to the system operators regarding available metered values for MW, MVAR, volt, amp, frequency, breaker status indication as it relates to network integration transmission service and distribution service and all other information deemed necessary by the Transmission Provider for safe and reliable operation. The Transmission Customer's equipment must comply with all applicable Federal and State environmental requirements to the extent they impact the operation of the Transmission Provider's system. d. The Transmission Customer shall operate all of its equipment and facilities connected to the Transmission Provider's system in a safe and efficient manner and in accordance with Good Utility Practice. e. Such representatives shall provide reasonable advance notice as well as make themselves known to the Transmission Customer's personnel, state the object of their visit, and conduct themselves in a manner that will not interfere with the construction or operation of the Transmission Customer's facilities. The Transmission Provider will have control such that it may open or close the circuit breaker or disconnect and place safety grounds at the Point(s) of Delivery, or at the station, if the Point(s) of Delivery is remote from the station for emergency situations or mutually agreed planned operations. 6. Each Point of Delivery shall have a unique identifier, meter location, meter number, metered voltage, terms on meter compensation and, the actual or, if not currently in service, the projected in service year. 7. The Transmission Provider may request that the Transmission Customer test, calibrate, verify or validate the data link, metering, data acquisition, transmission, protective, or other equipment or software owned by the Transmission Customer, consistent with the Transmission Customer's routine obligation to maintain its equipment and facilities, or for the purposes of trouble shooting problems on the network facilities. The Transmission Customer will be responsible for the cost to test, calibrate, verify or validate the equipment or software. d. The Transmission Provider shall have the right to inspect the tests, calibrations, verifications and validations of the Transmission Customer's data link, metering, data acquisition, transmission, protective, or other equipment or other software connected to the Transmission Provider's system. e. The Transmission Customer, at the Transmission Provider's request, shall supply the Transmission Provider with a copy of the installation, test, and calibration records of the data link, metering, data acquisition, transmission, protective, or other equipment or other software owned by the Transmission Customer and connected to the Transmission Provider's system. f. The Transmission Provider shall have the right, at the Transmission Customer's expense, to monitor the factory acceptance test, the field acceptance test, and the installation of any metering, data acquisition, transmission, protective or other equipment or software installed on facilities directly connected to the Transmission Provider's system. 8. The Transmission Customer's equipment and facilities as they relate to network integration transmission service and distribution service shall be subject to all applicable emergency operation standards consistent with Good Utility Practice required of and by the Transmission Provider to operate in an interconnected transmission network. b. The Transmission Provider reserves the right to have the system operators take whatever actions or inactions they deem reasonably necessary during emergency operating conditions to: (i) preserve the integrity of the Transmission System, (ii) limit or prevent damage, (iii) expedite restoration of service, or (iv) preserve public safety. 9. If and when the Transmission Customer's generation facility that is directly connected to the Transmission Provider's system is not producing electricity, the Transmission Customer's generation facility must obtain station service capacity and energy from the retail franchise utility providing service. Station Service will comply with NESC and will not be tied in such a way that a backfeed into the Transmission Provider's system can occur. c. Protection Requirements: Protection requirements are defined in the Transmission Provider's standard interconnection contract and in VELCO, ISO New England, and NPCC documents as may be adopted or amended from time to time. d. Operational Obligations: i. ISO New England may require the generators to be equipped for Automatic Generation Control ("AGC"). The Transmission Customer will be responsible for all costs associated with installing and maintaining an AGC system on the Transmission Customer's generators that are directly connected to the Transmission Provider's system. ii. The Transmission Provider will use due diligence to resolve the problems to allow the generator to return to the operating level prior to the Transmission Provider's notice to reduce generation. iii. All operations (including start-up, shutdown and determination of hourly generation) for generators directly connected to the Transmission Provider's system will be coordinated with ISO New England, VELCO, or the Transmission Provider's Designated Agent. e. Coordination of Operations: i. The Transmission Customer shall furnish the Transmission Provider with generator annual maintenance schedules and advise the Transmission Provider if its Network Resource is capable of participation in system restoration and/or if it has black start capability. ii. The Transmission Provider reserves the right to specify turbine and/or generator control (e.g., droop) settings as determined by the System Impact or Facilities Study or subsequent studies. The Transmission Customer agrees to comply with such specifications by the Transmission Provider at the Transmission Customer's expense. iii. If the generator is not dispatchable by ISO New England, the Transmission Customer shall notify the Transmission Provider at least 48 hours in advance of its intent to take its resource temporarily off-line and its intent to resume generation. In circumstances such as forced outages, the Transmission Customer shall notify the Transmission Provider as promptly as possible of the Network Resource's temporary interruption of generation and/or transmission. 11. Service for Delivery to Load: The following Terms and Conditions are specific to Service for Delivery to Load: a. Power Factor Requirement: The Transmission Customer agrees to maintain an overall Load Power Factor and reactive power supply within predefined sub-areas as measured at the Point(s) of Delivery within ranges specified by the Transmission Provider, VELCO, and ISO New England criteria, rules and standards consistent with Good Utility Practice which identify the power factor levels that must be maintained throughout the applicable sub-area for each anticipated level of total NEPOOL load. ISO New England may revise the power factor limits required from time to time. If the Transmission Customer lacks the capability to maintain the Load Power Factor within the ranges specified, the Transmission Provider may install, at the Transmission Customer's expense, reactive compensation equipment necessary to ensure proper load power factor at the Point(s) of Delivery. b. Failure to perform: If the Transmission Customer fails to carry out its obligations under this Agreement the matter will be subject to the dispute resolution procedures of Section 12 of the Network Tariff. 13. System Operations: Notwithstanding any of the above, the following specific operating procedures must be adhered to. All safety and communication protocols will be maintained. a. Separation: The Transmission Provider, at its sole discretion, shall install a means of separation of the interconnected systems at the Transmission Customer's sole expense. 14. The Transmission Customer shall supply accurate and reliable information to the system operators regarding available metered values for MW, MVAR, volt, amp, frequency, breaker status indication as it relates to network integration transmission service and distribution service and all other information deemed necessary by the Transmission Provider for safe and reliable operation. Information will be exchanged electronically where possible. 3. Operational Obligations at Point(s) of Delivery: The Transmission Customer shall request permission from the system operators prior to opening and/or closing circuit breakers, which could impact the Transmission Provider's service, per applicable switching and operating procedures. The Transmission Customer shall carry out all switching orders from the Transmission Provider, VELCO, ISO New England, or the Transmission Provider's designee in a timely manner. a. The Transmission Customer shall reasonably balance the load at the Point(s) of Delivery such that the differences in the individual phase currents are acceptable to the Transmission Provider. b. The Transmission Customer's equipment shall conform with harmonic distortion and voltage fluctuation standards that conform to Good Utility Practice. c. The Transmission Customer's equipment must comply with all applicable Federal and State environmental requirements to the extent they impact the operation of the Transmission Provider's system. d. The Transmission Customer shall operate all of its equipment and facilities connected to the Transmission Provider's system in a safe and efficient manner and in accordance with Good Utility Practice. e. The Transmission Customer is responsible for supplying voltage regulation equipment on its subtransmission and distribution facilities. 4. Notice of Transmission Service Interruptions: If at any time, in the reasonable exercise of the system operator's judgment, operation of the Transmission Customer's equipment adversely affects the quality of service or interferes with the safe and reliable operation of the system, the Transmission Provider may discontinue transmission service until the condition has been corrected. Unless the system operators perceive that an emergency exists or the risk of an emergency is imminent, the system operators shall give the Transmission Customer reasonable notice of its intention to discontinue transmission service and, where practical, allow suitable time for the Transmission Customer to remove the interfering condition. The Transmission Provider's judgment with regard to the discontinuance of service under this paragraph shall be made in accordance with Good Utility Practice. In the case of such discontinuance, the Transmission Provider shall immediately confer with the Transmission Customer regarding the conditions causing such discontinuance and its recommendation concerning timely correction thereof. 5. Access and Control: Properly accredited representatives of the Transmission Provider shall at all reasonable times have access to the Transmission Customer's facilities to make reasonable inspections and obtain information required in connection with this Network Tariff. Such representatives shall provide reasonable advance notice as well as make themselves known to the Transmission Customer's personnel, state the object of their visit, and conduct themselves in a manner that will not interfere with the construction or operation of the Transmission Customer's facilities. The Transmission Provider will have control such that it may open or close the circuit breaker or disconnect and place safety grounds at the Point(s) of Delivery, or at the station, if the Point(s) of Delivery is remote from the station for emergency situations or mutually agreed planned operations. 6. Point(s) of Delivery or Remote Delivery Point(s): Network Transmission service will be delivered by the Transmission Provider at the Point(s) of Delivery as specified in the Customer's Service Agreement, and as amended from time to time. Each Point of Delivery shall have a unique identifier, meter location, meter number, metered voltage, terms on meter compensation and, the actual or, if not currently in service, the projected in service year. 7. Maintenance of Equipment at Point(s) of Delivery: a. Unless otherwise agreed, the Transmission Provider will own all metering equipment. b. The Transmission Customer shall maintain all of its equipment and facilities connected to the Transmission Provider's system in a safe and efficient manner and in accordance with manufacturers' recommendations, Good Utility Practice, applicable regulations, and requirements of the Transmission Provider, VELCO, ISO New England, and NPCC. c. The Transmission Provider may request that the Transmission Customer test, calibrate, verify or validate the data link, metering, data acquisition, transmission, protective, or other equipment or software owned by the Transmission Customer, consistent with the Transmission Customer's routine obligation to maintain its equipment and facilities, or for the purposes of trouble shooting problems on the network facilities. The Transmission Customer will be responsible for the cost to test, calibrate, verify or validate the equipment or software. d. The Transmission Provider shall have the right to inspect the tests, calibrations, verifications and validations of the Transmission Customer's data link, metering, data acquisition, transmission, protective, or other equipment or other software connected to the Transmission Provider's system. e. The Transmission Customer, at the Transmission Provider's request, shall supply the Transmission Provider with a copy of the installation, test, and calibration records of the data link, metering, data acquisition, transmission, protective, or other equipment or other software owned by the Transmission Customer and connected to the Transmission Provider's system. f. The Transmission Provider shall have the right, at the Transmission Customer's expense, to monitor the factory acceptance test, the field acceptance test, and the installation of any metering, data acquisition, transmission, protective or other equipment or software installed on facilities directly connected to the Transmission Provider's system. 8. Emergency System Operations: a. The Transmission Customer's equipment and facilities as they relate to network integration transmission service and distribution service shall be subject to all applicable emergency operation standards consistent with Good Utility Practice required of and by the Transmission Provider to operate in an interconnected transmission network. b. The Transmission Provider reserves the right to have the system operators take whatever actions or inactions they deem reasonably necessary during emergency operating conditions to: (i) preserve the integrity of the Transmission System, (ii) limit or prevent damage, (iii) expedite restoration of service, or (iv) preserve public safety. 9. Cost Responsibility: The Transmission Customer shall be responsible for all reasonable costs incurred by the Transmission Provider relative to the Transmission Customer's facilities and in accordance with Good Utility Practice. Some costs may be allocated to several Transmission Customers. If the method for allocating costs is not clearly defined, then the method for allocation will be at the Transmission Provider's discretion. 10. Service For a Network Resource: The following Terms and Conditions apply to service for any new or future generator Network Resource as it relates to network integration transmission service and distribution service. a. Voltage or Reactive Control Requirements: i. Unless directed otherwise, the Transmission Customer will operate its interconnected generation facility(ies) with an automatic voltage regulator(s). The voltage regulator will control voltage at the Point(s) of Receipt consistent with the range of voltage scheduled by the Transmission Provider, the Transmission Provider's agent, VELCO, or ISO New England. ii. At the discretion of the Transmission Provider, the Transmission Provider's agent, VELCO, or ISO New England, the Transmission Customer may be directed to deactivate the automatic voltage regulator and to supply reactive power per a schedule provided by the Transmission Provider, the Transmission Provider's agent, VELCO, or ISO New England. iii. If the Transmission Customer has not installed capacity sufficient to operate its generation facility consistent with recommendations of the Transmission Provider resulting from the System Impact and Facilities Studies or fails to operate at such capacity, the Transmission Provider may install, at the Transmission Customer's expense, reactive compensation equipment necessary to ensure the proper voltage or reactive supply at the Point(s) of Receipt. b. Station Service: When the Transmission Customer's generation facility that is directly connected to the Transmission Provider's system is producing electricity, the Transmission Customer's generation facility must supply its own station service power. If and when the Transmission Customer's generation facility that is directly connected to the Transmission Provider's system is not producing electricity, the Transmission Customer's generation facility must obtain station service capacity and energy from the retail franchise utility providing service. Station Service will comply with NESC and will not be tied in such a way that a backfeed into the Transmission Provider's system can occur. c. Protection Requirements: Protection requirements are defined in the Transmission Provider's standard interconnection contract and in VELCO, ISO New England, and NPCC documents as may be adopted or amended from time to time. d. Operational Obligations: i. ISO New England may require the generators to be equipped for Automatic Generation Control ("AGC"). The Transmission Customer will be responsible for all costs associated with installing and maintaining an AGC system on the Transmission Customer's generators that are directly connected to the Transmission Provider's system. ii. The Transmission Provider retains the right to require reduced generation at times when system conditions present transmission restrictions or otherwise adversely affect the Transmission Provider's other customers. The Transmission Provider will use due diligence to resolve the problems to allow the generator to return to the operating level prior to the Transmission Provider's notice to reduce generation. iii. All operations (including start-up, shutdown and determination of hourly generation) for generators directly connected to the Transmission Provider's system will be coordinated with ISO New England, VELCO, or the Transmission Provider's Designated Agent. e. Coordination of Operations: i. The Transmission Customer shall furnish the Transmission Provider with generator annual maintenance schedules and advise the Transmission Provider if its Network Resource is capable of participation in system restoration and/or if it has black start capability. ii. The Transmission Provider reserves the right to specify turbine and/or generator control (e.g., droop) settings as determined by the System Impact or Facilities Study or subsequent studies. The Transmission Customer agrees to comply with such specifications by the Transmission Provider at the Transmission Customer's expense. iii. If the generator is not dispatchable by ISO New England, the Transmission Customer shall notify the Transmission Provider at least 48 hours in advance of its intent to take its resource temporarily off-line and its intent to resume generation. In circumstances such as forced outages, the Transmission Customer shall notify the Transmission Provider as promptly as possible of the Network Resource's temporary interruption of generation and/or transmission. 11. Service for Delivery to Load: The following Terms and Conditions are specific to Service for Delivery to Load: a. Power Factor Requirement: The Transmission Customer agrees to maintain an overall Load Power Factor and reactive power supply within predefined sub-areas as measured at the Point(s) of Delivery within ranges specified by the Transmission Provider, VELCO, and ISO New England criteria, rules and standards consistent with Good Utility Practice which identify the power factor levels that must be maintained throughout the applicable sub-area for each anticipated level of total NEPOOL load. The Transmission Customer agrees to maintain Load Power Factor and reactive power requirements within the range specified by the Transmission Provider, VELCO, and ISO New England as appropriate for the sub-area based on total NEPOOL load during that hour. ISO New England may revise the power factor limits required from time to time. If the Transmission Customer lacks the capability to maintain the Load Power Factor within the ranges specified, the Transmission Provider may install, at the Transmission Customer's expense, reactive compensation equipment necessary to ensure proper load power factor at the Point(s) of Delivery. b. Protection Requirements: The Transmission Customer's relay and protection systems at the point(s) of delivery must comply with all applicable Transmission Provider, VELCO, ISO New England, and NPCC criteria, rules, procedures, guidelines, standards and requirements as may be adopted or amended from time to time and in accordance with Good Utility Practice. c. Operational Obligations: The Transmission Customer shall be responsible for operating and maintaining security of its electric system in a manner that avoids adverse impact to the Transmission Provider's or others' interconnected systems and complies with all applicable Transmission Provider, VELCO, ISO New England, and NPCC operating criteria, rules, procedures, guidelines and interconnection standards as may be amended or adopted from time to time. These actions include, but are not limited to: Voltage Reduction Load Shedding; Under Frequency Load Shedding; Block Load Shedding; Dead Station Tripping; Transferring Load Between Point(s) of Delivery; Implementing Voluntary Load Reductions Including Interruptible Customers; Starting Stand-by Generation; Permitting Transmission Provider Controlled Service Restoration Following Supply Delivery Contingencies on Transmission Provider Facilities. 12. Failure to perform: If the Transmission Customer fails to carry out its obligations under this Agreement the matter will be subject to the dispute resolution procedures of Section 12 of the Network Tariff. 13. System Operations: Notwithstanding any of the above, the following specific operating procedures must be adhered to. All safety and communication protocols will be maintained. a. Lines of Communication: The Transmission Customer will provide contact information to the Transmission Provider for operation of the systems. b. Operational Control: The Transmission Provider shall have full and exclusive operational control of all switches and equipment that connect the systems of the Transmission Provider and Transmission Customer. c. Separation: The Transmission Provider, at its sole discretion, shall install a means of separation of the interconnected systems at the Transmission Customer's sole expense. 14. System Maps and Updates: The Transmission Customer shall provide to the Transmission Provider electrical diagrams and routine updates of the Transmission Customer's system as it relates to the point(s) of delivery in support of the safe, reliable operations of the interconnected systems.

RATE SCHEDULE FOR PASS-THROUGH BILLING TO WOODSVILLE WATER AND LIGHT DEPARTMENT
I. The Company agrees to provide pass-through billing to Woodsville Water and Light Department ("WWLD") for Regional Network Service ("RNS") provided to WWLD by ISO New England Inc. ("ISO-NE") and Local Network Service ("LNS") provided to WWLD by National Grid or, in rare circumstances, by Vermont Transco, LLC ("VTransco"), metered at the Ryegate substation delivery point1 for the period of November 1, 2007 through April 25, 2011. II. ISO-NE and National Grid deliveries to WWLD at the Ryegate substation are comingled with their deliveries at that delivery point for two other wholesale distribution systems and a small amount of Company load. III. The Company shall pass through to WWLD the applicable LNS and associated ancillary service charges from National Grid and RNS and associated ancillary service charges from ISO-NE assessed to the Company for the benefit of WWLD in proportion to the WWLD load share of such costs billed to the Company. This pass-through of charges shall be calculated based on the WWLD load at the time of the transmission peak of the applicable transmission provider. The WWLD share of such charges is calculated by determining all cost items that are based on load and multiplying that total by the ratio of WWLD load to total Company load delivered by National Grid.2
IV. In the rare case that switching occurs in any month as a result of an outage such that VTransco is the transmission provider for a period of time instead of National Grid, WWLD shall pay LNS and associated ancillary service charges for that month according to one of the following, based on the applicable condition: (a) if VTransco and not National Grid charges were applicable, WWLD shall pay VTransco charges instead of National Grid; (b) if neither VTransco nor National Grid charges were applicable, WWLD shall pay no applicable LNS and associated ancillary service charges; or (c) if both VTransco and National Grid charges were applicable, WWLD shall pay LNS and associated ancillary service charges for both VTransco and National Grid. The pass-through of charges to WWLD shall be calculated based on the methodology described in Section III, above.
V. The method of calculating applicable charges is described, and an example calculation is provided, in Attachment A to this Rate Schedule. Attachment B to this Rate Schedule includes a Transmission Billing Agreement between the Company and WWLD that addresses the pass-through billing for a portion of the relevant time period. The term "Company" as used herein denotes CVPS, which provided the pass-through billing in the relevant period. CVPS has since been merged with and into GMP.
C:\NRPortbl\DC\NALLEN\80510116_1.DOCX 42422-0005 DC\80510116.1 1 The metering point is at the Company's B-37 breaker at the Ryegate substation. This substation was jointly owned by Central Vermont Public Service Corporation ("CVPS") and Green Mountain Power Corporation ("GMP") prior to October 1, 2012 and includes a 34.5/46 kV transformer to step up to the CVPS subtransmission system voltage. Ryegate is normally connected radially to the McIndoes Falls substation, which is the delivery point from National Grid to GMP at 34.5 kV. Effective October 1, 2012, GMP owns the Ryegate substation. 2 Prior to October 1, 2012 National Grid delivered power to CVPS at the Ryegate and Gilman delivery points. ---------------
